<item>
            <title>[LU-18978] Need to provide yum/dnf reposiories for Lustre</title>
                <link>https://jira.whamcloud.com/browse/LU-18978</link>
                <project id="10000" key="LU">Lustre</project>
                    <description>&lt;p&gt;With more inflow of new people into Lustre outside of our traditional HPC markets we need to make it more accessible.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;As recent posts o nteh lustre-discuss show, people find it challenging to build Lustre esp. using outdated materials on lustre.org wiki&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;As such we should add repositories for common distros we expect Lustre users to use like rhel/rocku 8.10 and rhel/rocky/9.6 and the like (and some ubuntu?)&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Nvidia drivers/cuds is a good example here, they have a repo you just install and then enable and then just &quot;dnf install lustre&quot;, reboot and you have a fully functioning system.&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;See their example here: &lt;a href=&quot;https://docs.nvidia.com/datacenter/tesla/driver-installation-guide/index.html#network-repository-installation&quot; class=&quot;external-link&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow noopener&quot;&gt;https://docs.nvidia.com/datacenter/tesla/driver-installation-guide/index.html#network-repository-installation&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Once that is in place we should then update the docs to refer to this new easier method&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Also for fedora, if we ever decide t osupport that, we could register a copr and then use that for our packages.&lt;/p&gt;</description>
